<h4>DAO Governance</h4>
  <h5>Pros</h5>
    <ul>
      <li>Participant responses are immutable and verifiable.
        <ul>
          <li>Users can vote for, against, or abstain from proposals. Responses are recorded on the blockchain.</li>
          <li>While blockchain voting is not limited to the scope of DAO participation, vote immutability has the potential to demonstrate transparency and legitimacy of results.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li>Users are empowered to have an impact on governance and finance.
        <ul>
          <li>This gives opportunities for communities to have a direct impact on important decisions without a middleman or central authority.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li>Participants maintain autonomy over their votes.
        <ul>
          <li>Sole voting power lies with the user.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

  <br>

  <h5>Cons</h5>
    <ul>
      <li>Wealth buys influence
        <ul>
          <li>Influence through wealth accumulation creates a "digital plutocracy", where the wealthiest participants have disproportionate influence.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li>Human Nature
        <ul>
          <li>Users are often incentivized to always vote in their own financial interests, stalling progress.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li>Development Team Centralization
        <ul>
          <li>DAO development teams can still disregard the will of the community.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

  <br>

  <h5>Challenges</h5>
    <ul>
      <li>"Worthless governance tokens"
        <ul>
          <li>DAO tokens are commonly used for raising funds for projects through retail investors. Average token price performances resemble “pump and dump” trends, which has drawn skepticism and critique in and outside of the Web 3 space.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Sybil attacks
        <ul>
          <li>Community members creating multiple "sock puppet" accounts to manipulate votes or engage in other fraudulent activity.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Voter privacy
        <ul>
          <li>While there could be some public benefit to voting transparency, there are other cases where the privacy of an individual's vote should also be protected. In the current state of DAOs, all user voting data is publicly available.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

  <br>

  <h5>Solutions</h5>
    <ul>
      <li>Account abstraction for user privacy and sybil resistance
        <ul>
          <li>User authenticity and individuality can be verified by using technologies like zero knowledge proofs, which can prove that users match certain criteria for voting eligibility, while not revealing their identity to the public.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Smart Contract Security audits
        <ul>
          <li>Smart contract security audits enhance both DAOs and the broader Web3 ecosystem by identifying and mitigating vulnerabilities in code. For DAOs, audits bolster governance integrity, preventing attacks and ensuring token-holder interests.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

  <br>

  <h5>DAOs gone wrong</h5>
    <ul>
      <li>Tornado Cash DAO exploit
        <ul>
          <li>Tornado Cash DAO suffered a hack where an attacker exploited a proposal, taking control of the project and draining tokens.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Arbitrum team's management of funds
        <ul>
          <li>Arbitrum team preemptively spent tokens before the results of a DAO vote where the community rejected the spending of $1 billion worth of ARB tokens.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>"The DAO hack"
        <ul>
          <li>The Ethereum DAO hack involved an attacker exploiting vulnerabilities to drain a significant amount of Ether from the Decentralized Autonomous Organization (DAO). This incident led to a contentious debate within the Ethereum community, resulting in a contentious hard fork to reverse the hack and recover the stolen funds.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
